![](https://polepedia.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/Scissor-Sit-Pole-Dance-Dictionary.gif "Scissor Sit - Pole Dance Dictionary")

**Difficulty:** Intermediate

**Category:** Spin

**Type:** Spin Pole, Static Pole

**Points of Contact:** 4

**Also Known As:**

* Split Sit
* V Sit

TheÂ **Scissor Sit**is a unique pole pose that relies on the opening of the legs after reaching the standard pole sit position. This unique sit is an excellent way to pull together a new shape in your latest routine.

[![](https://polepedia.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/xpole-ad-horizontal-800-%C3%97-328-px.png "xpole ad polepedia")](https://xpoleus.com/shop-all/poles/xpert-pro/xpert-pro-px/affiliate/illunadin/?campaign=move)

**How to Perform the Scissor Sit**

**Move Steps**

1. Start on the pole in a basic pole sit position.
2. Slowly, spread the legs apart while keeping the pressure from the pole against the legs and keeping the pelvis tilted.
3. Hold the chest up and hold the pose for as long as you would like.

**Safety Tips**

* Always keep one hand on the pole at all times and maintain a strong tilt in the pelvis to keep the tension between the pole and your legs.

**Common Mistakes**

* **Having Trouble Spreading Legs**: If you are having trouble spreading your legs, then you may consider starting from a pole sit with the knees bent. From here, you can bring your top knee up and your bottom knee down, then extend. This helps remove the fright of spreading the legs and potentially losing contact with the pole in an extended position.

